sentences.content: The shoes from Japan arrived.
I gave 2 pairs to my old track coach, Bill Bowerman.
I loved and feared Bowerman the same way I felt about my father.
Oddly, they were both named Bill.
On January 25, 1964, I met with Bowerman.
He wanted a dozen pairs of Tiger shoes for his team and to become my business partner.
Next, I met with Bowerman's lawyer, named Jaqua.
Jaqua said "50-50 is not so hot for the Coach."
They did not want to be in charge.
They asked to split the deal 51-49.
I trusted him.
I wrote Onitsuka and asked to be the distributor of Tiger Shoes in the western United States.
I asked them to send 300 pairs of Tigers.
I had to ask my dad for more money.
He thought I was wasting my time.
Both of my parents grew up in poverty.
My parents were opposites.
When their opposite personalities caused problems, my dad drank, and my mother turned to stone.
When my father accused me of "jackassing around," my mother asked to buy a pair of shoes.
My father decided to loan me the money.
In April, a letter came from Mr. Miyazaki saying I could be the distributor for Onitsuka in the West.
I quit my accounting job and sold shoes out of the trunk of my Valiant.
I couldn't write orders fast enough.
People would write to me to buy shoes.
Without trying, my mail-order business was born.
Sometimes, people would show up at my parents' house.
In July 1964, I sold out my first shipment.
I wrote to Tiger and ordered 900 more pairs of shoes.
The cost was $3,000.
My father told me the Bank of Dad is now closed.
I went to Los Angeles to try to sell more shoes.
I attended a track meet and ran into an old running friend, Jeff Johnson.
On weekends he sold Adidas.
I told him to work for me instead.
He was getting married soon and said no.
I was as happy as ever.
Then, I got a letter from a high school wrestling coach, Mr. Hanhasset.
He looked just like the Marlboro Man.
In the letter, Mr Hanhasset said he just came back from Japan, and the executives at Onitsuka, appointed him their exclusive American distributor.
He ordered me to stop.
I thought about giving up on my dream of selling shoes.
I couldn't.
I flew back to Japan and met with Onitsuka.
My parents supported me.
I spent the flight reading How to Do Business with the Japanese.
I couldn't let my emotions get in the way.
When I got to Japan, I called Onitsuka and left a message, "I'm here, and I request a meeting."
Mr. Onitsuka decided I could sell track shoes in the 13 western states.
The Marlboro Man could sell his wrestling shoes nationwide.
He could only sell track shoes on the East Coast.
